<DOC><DOCNO> AP880225-0233 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0018EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-China-Hepatitis     02-25 0189</FIRST><SECOND>AM-China-Hepatitis,0195</SECOND><HEAD>Seven Reported Dead in Shanghai From Hepatitis</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A hepatitis epidemic in Shanghai has killedseven people, but the number of new cases has dropped considerably,the pro-Beijing Hong Kong newspaper Ta Kung Pao reported Wednesday.   It quoted Wang Daomin, director of the Shanghai Public HealthBureau, as saying health officials verified seven deaths. Previousreports did not mention deaths.   The viral disease, commonly spread in food and water, causesinflammation of the liver, nausea, vomiting and fever.   Wang also was quoted as saying the number of new cases ofhepatitis A had dropped 80 percent from the height of the epidemic.   Shanghai officials earlier put the number sickened in the2-month-old outbreak at 16,000. Western doctors there said thenumber could be as high as 40,000. The epidemic was blamed oncontaminated clams harvested from polluted coastal waters.   China's official English-language newspaper China Daily saidBeijing health authorities launched a city-wide sanitationinspection.   In Canton, capital of southern Guangdong province, healthofficials warned people to refrain from shaking hands, to washtheir hands when visiting others and to avoid eating river snails.</TEXT></DOC>